manland, Sweden":"Södermanland, Sweden","Rekarne, Södermanland, Sweden":"Rekarne, Södermanland, Sweden","Sweden":"Sweden","Husby Rekarne Sodermanland":"Husby-Rekarne, Södermanland, Sweden","Floda, Södermanland, Sweden":"Floda, Södermanland, Sweden","Floda, Södermanland, Sverige":"Floda, Södermanland, Sweden","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kagge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Kegel  ,   Kagel  , or <b>Kögel</b> (see   Kogel  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Kegel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gunter, Franz, Fritz, Grete, Ute, Wilhelm.","German and Dutch: from Middle High German and Middle Dutch <i>kegel</i> ‘skittle, pin’, hence a nickname for an inveterate skittles or bowls player. The term also denoted an illegitimate child (hence the phrase (still current) <i>mit Kind und Kegel</i> ‘with all the family’); in Early New High German (15th century) took on the meaning ‘uncouth person’.","Slovenian: nickname from <i>kegelj</i> ‘skittle, pin’, a word of German origin (see 1 above). In North America, this surname may also be an altered form of the variant <b>Kegelj</b> and possibly also <b>Kegl</b>."]}]},{"name":"Erland","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old Norse personal name, originally a byname from <i>örlendr</i> ‘foreigner, stranger’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mattsson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Anders, Erik, Matts, Nils, Bjorn, Gunvor, Per, Sten, Thor, Thorvald, Torvald.","Swedish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Matts</i>, a short form of <i>Matthias</i> or <i>Mattheus</i> (see   Matthew  ). Compare   Matson   and   Mattson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mattson","meanings":["Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish   Mattsson  .","Americanized form of Danish and Norwegian   Mattsen   and   Madsen  , cognates of 1.","English (mainly Yorkshire and Derbyshire): variant of   Matson  ."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1702076,"age":51,"year":"1436","julianDay":2245548,"title":"The Engelbrekt Rebellion","description":"Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson, a Swedish mine owner and statesman, led a rebellion against Eric of Pomerania, King of the Kalmar Union. Sweden was upset with the Danes' interference with Swedish exports and unjust collection of taxes. The Engelbrekt Rebellion led to the deposing of Eric of Pomerania and the eventual dissolution of the Kalmar Union.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Erland Mattsson Kagge was born about 1385, in Floda, Södermanland, Sweden, his father, Matts Erlandsson Kagg, was 27 and his mother, Mrs Matts Erlandsson Kagg, was 22. He married Gertrud before 1451, in Södermanland, Sweden. He died in 1472, in Rekarne, Södermanland, Sweden, at the age of 88."},"et":{"about 1385–1472":"umbes 1385–1472","1385–1472":"1385–1472","1385–1454":"1385–1454","1422–Female":"1422–Surnud","1426–1473":"1426–1473","1435–1500":"1435–1500","1437–1473":"1437–1473","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","befo